The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Taj GVK focus on south

 SOHINI MOOKHERJEA

 Room for more: The Taj Krishna in Hyderabad

 Calcutta, Feb. 12: Taj GVK Hotels and Resorts has lined up expansion plans worth Rs 400 crore, including a foray into service apartments.

 It will focus mainly on the south, which officials said has one of the highest occupancy rates in the country. In the north, only exception is the property in Chandigarh where the occupancy rates are high.

 The funds will be raised through a debt-equity ratio of 2:1. The company will acquire new properties and upgrade and diversify existing ones.

 The company has three properties in Hyderabad, which includes two of its own ? Taj Krishna and Taj Residency. Taj Banjara is on an operating lease of 33 years.

 Taj Krishna, spread over 10 acres, has 261 rooms and the company wants to add another 125, officials said. Taj Krishna is a luxury property, while the rest are business hotels.

 Service apartments with 65 luxury rooms are also coming up. The company expects the whole project to be completed in two years, including the apartments at a cost of Rs 120 crore.

 Taj GVK has acquired a partly built property in Chennai, which will be converted into a business hotel with 250 rooms by March 2007. The investment in this project will range between Rs 110 crore and Rs 120 crore.

 The Hyderabad properties of Taj GVK have occupancy rates between 85 and 90 per cent with the city?s booming industry and information technology scenario. 

 According to a market survey done by the company, the Chennai property should average between 60 and 70 per cent rate of occupancy.

 The company plans to renovate Taj Residency to a luxury category of palace hotels, which also has 7 acres for further expansion.

 The Residency has 151 rooms to which would be added another 125 and the whole premises redecorated and renovated at a cost of Rs 100 crore within the next two years.

 A fourth property has been acquired on a 100-year lease in Hyderabad which would be developed into a business hotel of 189 rooms in the next two years at a cost ranging between Rs 60 crore and Rs 70 crore. 




